reviewText: CM Punk VS Randy (B)orton in a Last Man Standing Match: Very good much, ending was typical Orton. Hitting an awesome top rope RKO to defeat the leader of the Nexus. It's hard to belive this PPV is a little over a year old. It seems I can't remember jack about the storylines, then again i'm not attached to WWE like I was when I was younger.Tables Match for the US Title, Champion Sheamus VS Kofi Kingston: This match had some neat counters but the crowd was dead. Booker on commentary is obnoxious as he keeps on saying Kingston has to give up dancing in order to become an elite wrestler.  Kingston wins in the belt in the end in a good match, it wasn't bad but nothing anyone remembers.Country Whipping Match, JR & Jerry Lawler VS Jack Swagger & Michael Cole: Cole is one of the reason's why the current WWE product sucks. For nearly a year, he'd put down so many wreslters. While a heel commentator should that, it was just down right annoying. This match sucked and Cole wins again. I hope he follows the likes of The Coach & Admele and leaves WWE.Falls Count Anywhere Match, Cody Rhodes VS Rey Mysterio: Match of the night. One of the better hardcore matches WWE has put on since the attitude era. A must watch.Loser Leaves WWE Match, Michelle McCool VS Layla: Never watched a diva's match, not even in TNA or ROH. Never have, never will, skip.Ladder Match for the world title: Belt was vacated when Edge retired. I was cheering for Christian and it seemed to be going that way into the PPV. Alberto Del Rio was going strong, although I think WWE pushed him way to soon. Anyways, Brodus Clay made an apperance before he became a dinosaur and he bleeds heavily. Match was good, Edge comes out and distracts Del Rio as Christian realizes his dreams and captures the belt. Sadly, two days later he would lose it to (B)orton on Smackdown. Lots of fans complained and I don't think we'll see anymore short title reigns for a long time.Lumberjack Match for the tag titles: Big Show & Kane VS Wade Barrett & Ezikel Jackson, a decent match that went the way it should. The lumberjacks of course brawl afterwards.Triple Threat Cage Match for the WWE title featuring Champion Miz, John Cena, and John Morrison: I compare Morrison to Jeff Hardy, a small and very skilled wrestler that WWE doesn't push. While Hardy got his dues after paying his dues, Morrison just left WWE, and I don't seem him returning anytime soon. A very good match with Cena winning the belt in the end.Overall, Extreme Rules always seem to deliver and this one was no different. A must own WWE PPV.

reviewText: It should be noted that the SmackDown broadcast team of Josh Matthews & Booker T did the entire commentary throughout the night with Jerry Lawler joining them in the first match while Michael Cole would join them later in the broadcast.Last Man Standing Match: Randy Orton vs. C.M. Punk - Before the match got started, the RAW GM banned the New Nexus from ringside.  Both men took this brawl to the floor early before kendo sticks were pulled & used by both men.  At one point a chair was wedged in one of the corners of the ring to where Orton threw Punk into with so more force that he went through the chair onto the outside while later wearing it as a necktie when Punk threw him headfirst into the ringpost.  At times both men were beaten so badly that they barely made it up by the 10 count with moves like the RKO on the announce table (that didn't give), a GTS onto the steel steps, and another RKO from the top rope.  This was the third match in their series & just like the others, this didn't disappoint.Tables Match: United States Champion Sheamus vs. Kofi Kingston - This was a bonus match as Kofi scored a non-title win on RAW earlier in the week only to be attacked by Sheamus on SmackDown causing this match to be made & for those who follow politics, you'll get a chuckle out of Sheamus' interview.  They went back & forth as both men attempted to setup tables on the outside to use while also countering each other's attacks but Kofi was the true highlight here as he displayed very athletic ways to avoid hitting the tables various times throughout the match including changing his move attempt in midair when coming off the top rope to the floor.  This was a nice match.Country Whipping Match: Jerry Lawler & Jim Ross vs. Michael Cole & Jack Swagger - For those who don't remember the days of the Von Erich/Freebirds rivalry, this type of match allowed leather belt straps to be used as weapons.  Michael Cole came out in an outfit that I've only seen once before in the days of Lawler's ex-wife The Kat (and she looked better in it) which made for a comedic moment in the beginning.  This match was exactly what you would expect as Swagger & Lawler did most of the work here with Cole playing the coward of only coming in to get his shots when the others were down while Ross tried to put up a fight including even applying the anklelock to Swagger to the point where Cole didn't want to tag in when Swagger was reaching for one before eventually being forced in the ring & the anklelock himself.  Again this match was what you would expect but this was tons better than the WrestleMania match as this was played out with the right mix of everything.Falls Count Anywhere Match: Rey Mysterio vs. Cody Rhodes - Just like the opening match, this turned into a brawl right away as they fought from the ring to the stage area very early in the match.  The fight went into the crowd where Cody used the handrails in the middle of the isle to his advantage such as doing a modified version of Chris Jericho's old "Liontamer" submission with the railing.  They fought into the lobby area or the arena before taking the match back to the ring with Rey being hip tossed over the rail onto the floor in the process.  Cody went after Rey's face including slamming his face into the steps in this match before Mysterio did something that I don't remember seeing from him but got a "Great Muta" reference from Booker T in what turned out to be a great followup to their previous match at WrestleMania and SmackDown weeks later.No Disqualification/No Count Out/Loser Leaves WWE Match: Layla vs. Michelle McCool - LayCool finally broke up leading to this match as Michelle went right after Layla from the start by knocking her out of the ring during her entrance & slamming her into the announce table on the outside before Layla fought back with both girls brawling in & out of the ring.  At one point, Michelle was on the receiving end of a "Rude Awakening" neckbreaker that looked like she really snapped her neck.  The only thing I can really say that was bad is the fact that the ending came out of nowhere but told the good story of Layla doing what she had to do but didn't want to do all the way from the start of the match to after the match...and lets just say that after everything Michelle's done to the other divas, she got a taste of "Kharma" on her out of the WWE.World Championship/Ladder Match - For those who don't already know, Edge was forced to retire the week after WrestleMania & forfeited the World Championship in the process setting up this ladder match between the two top challengers.  There were plenty of spots (as expected) in this type of match such as Christian falling face first into a ladder after his legs were pulled from under him, Del Rio dropped arm first into a ladder & later using a "Hornswoggle" sized ladder to execute a armbreaker onto Christian off another ladder, a ladder wedged between the ring apron & the announce table resulting in Del Rio taking a very nasty landing on his spine, the appearance of Brodus Clay resulting in him having his own pool of blood on the outside, Del Rio doing a variation of his cross armbreaker using the stepladder, and the appearance of a "Rated R" jeep leading to a moment that a solid core group of fans have been waiting a long time to happen...at least in WWE.Lumberjack Match: Tag Team Champions Big Show & Kane vs. The Corre - This was another last minute bonus match with this team of The Corre consisting of Ezekel Jackson & Wade Barrett.  As typical with a lumberjack match, you had the heels beat down the babyfaces whenever they went on the outside leading to a funny moment in the ring where Show & Kane made some of them pay for it.  This match overall though was more of a backdrop for the continued problems within The Corre as Ezekel Jackson was dominate with his power before Barrett tagged himself in to hog the glory only for it to end up costing his team the match.Steel Cage Match: WWE Champion The Miz vs. John Cena vs. John Morrison - With The Miz's bad history with both of these men, he was easily singled out early before they turned on each other letting Miz use the "divide & conquer" strategy early in the match.  This was non-stop action as there were various moments when two men were fighting leaving the third man to attempting to leave the cage.  Morrison was able to showcase his parkor in various ways including a Starship Pain from the top of the cage, landing on the cage door in a way that hurt every man in the arena, & leaping from the top rope to the top of the cage leading to him & Cena doing a double superplex on Miz from the top of the cage that just made you cringe seeing how Miz landed.  With an appearance from the new & improved R-Truth along with Cena giving one heck of an Attitude Adjustment, we saw a great cage match here.The title of my review says it all here in that we got the action here that she should have gotten at WrestleMania as all the Mania rematches were just as good or even better than the matches we got at Mania.  There wasn't a bad or unwatchable match on here so this is an event worth going out of your way to see.

reviewText: Given how lackluster Wrestlemania was, Extreme Rules was a fairly good show.-Last Man Standing Match: CM Punk vs. Randy Orton: These two have had a great rivalry, their match at Wrestlemania was one of the few bright spots of that show. This was a pretty brutal match and the crowd was split in the beginning cheering for both men. Punk brings out a kendo stick, repeatedly hitting Orton with it, even going after his shoulder that has been injured in the past. Punk sets up a chair in the corner but gets swung into it head first. Punk hits a nice high kick but he takes a nasty backdrop onto the barricade, but makes it back up before the 10 count. Orton hits an RKO on the announce table but it doesn't break. Punk counters Ortons punt into a modified GTS on the steel steps, but Orton gets back up. Orton hits a top rope RKO and Punk is down for the count and Orton wins. 9/10.-Tables Match for the U.S. Title: Kofi Kingston vs. Sheamus (Champion): This is an added match and the crowd seemed dead. There were some nice spots like Kofi jumping onto the ropes to avoid going through a table. Kofi jumps off the top rope slamming Sheamus through a table to become the new U.S. champion. An ok but not great match, especially cause of the dead crowd. 5/10.-Nice backstage promo by the newly turned heel R-Truth, good idea to do something different with him.-Country Whipping Match: Jim Ross & Jerry Lawler vs. Michael Cole & Jack Swagger: Cole comes out covered in bubble wrap (you read that right) to absorb the impact of the leather straps used in this match. This is exactly what you'd expect with Lawler and Swagger carrying most of the match though Ross gets in some nice shots on Cole and Swagger. Ross does get a measure of revenge on Cole though he does get rolled up by Cole for the win. 6/10 and that's being generous.-Falls Count Anywhere Match: Rey Mysterio vs. Cody Rhodes: A vastly underated rivalry and this was a good match that went all over the arena, Rey hit a seated senton splash off the stage. The action even up the stands into the hallways where some of the crowd cheers them on and Rhodes hits a jumping kick off of a concession cart that got a nice "Holy S***" chant from the crowd. Rey hits a springboard dive from a concessions counter for a 2 count. Back in the ring Rey does a diving headbutt to Cody for 2. Rhodes has Rey up in the corner but Rey sprays some mist into Rhodes eyes, then hits the 619 and splash off the top rope for the win. 9/10.-Layla confronts the divas and apologizes for ever hurting any of them, since this could be her last match coming up.-Loser Leaves WWE Match: Michelle McCool vs. Layla: The 2 former Laycool members face off in what is easily the best women's match WWE has put in years. McCool is more vicious in the early going knocking Layla off the top rope and hitting a nice kick for 2. Layla fights back on the outside nailing McCool into the announce table, then hits a nice springboard dropkick for 2. McCool goes for a kick but misses jamming her knee into the barricade. Layla hits the Laid Out Diamond Dust off the top rope for the win. Layla hits a reverse neck stunner but McCool gets her foot on the bottom rope. McCool hits the Styles Clash I mean Faith Breaker and goes for the pin but Layla reverses it for the 3 count. Winner Layla, Michelle McCool is gone from WWE. 9/10. Michelle is crying in the ring, when Kharma's (TNA's Awesome Kong) music hits and she comes out staring down McCool and hits the Implant Buster laughing like a maniac then walks off. They show a shot of the divas looking on and they all look shocked.-Backstage Ricardo Rodriguez is practicing announcing Alberto Del Rio as the World Champion, Del Rio doesn't like it and makes him do it again.-Ladder Match for the vacant World Title: Alberto Del Rio vs. Christian: Its Del Rio's destiny vs. The Instant Classic's quest for his first world title (if you ignore his 2 title reigns during his 3 year run with TNA that is). This was a good ladder match that had plenty of uses of the ladders, but first there is some good wrestling by both Del Rio and Christian. Del Rio gets hotshotted into the the ladder in the corner that looked like it jacked up his elbow. Del Rio gets backdropped into the ring smashing his back into a ladder. Nice jumping kick by Del Rio around a ladder kicking Christian who falls down on the ladder jamming his side. Christian hits a spear and goes up the ladder but Del Rio pulls his legs through and traps Christian in the ladder. Del Rio jumps from the top rope and hits the ladder on the outside as Christian moves out of the way. Brodius Clay makes his way out to prevent Christian from getting the title, Clay gets knocked to the outside but Del Rio locks on the cross arm breaker while Christians arm in a ladder. Del Rio almost has the title when Edge comes out in a jeep distracting him, Christian knocks Del Rio to the outside, and grabs the title to become the new World Champion. 9/10. Christian and Edge celebrate the win in the ring.-Lumberjack Match for the Tag Team Titles: Big Show & Kane (Champions) vs. Wade Barrett and Ezekiel Jackson: The lumberjacks include Heath Slater, Justin Gabriel, Tyler Reks, The Usos, Primo, Evan Bourne, Yoshi Tatsu, Koslov, Santino Marella and some guys whom I have no clue who they are. This is a standard tag match, Big Show chops Barrett then Kane comes in with a low dropkick. Barrett to the outside, gets right back in and eats a sideslam. Kane gets nailed by some lumberjacks and Big Show knocks like 4 of them down. Zeke is in and uses massive clotheslines and forearms to wear down Kane. Show is tagged in and Zeke nails a very impressive slam on Show, Barrett tags himself in but eats a chokeslam and Big Show pins him for the win to retain the tag titles. 7/10. A post match brawl occurs between the lumberjacks and Slater and Gabriel both take stereo chokeslams.-Triple Threat Cage Match for the WWE Championship: John Morrison vs. John Cena vs. The Miz (Champion): There's some double teaming on the Miz by Cena and Morrison, and later in the match they hit a double suplex on Miz from the top of the cage. Cena lock on the STFU on Miz who almost gets out the cage door before Cena pulls him back in. Morrison pulls off some impressive moves in this match, like a double jump spring kick and hitting Starship Pain from the top of the cage onto both Cena and Miz. Morrison goes for the cage door and R-Truth comes in and puts him back in the cage, then enters the cage beating up Morrision some, even hitting the axe kick on Cena before climbing over the top and leaving. Miz and Cena battle at the top of the cage and Cena hits a top rope AA and becomes the new WWE Champion.... again..... ugh. 9/10 for the match.-Extreme Rules was a good show and is worth getting on DVD.

reviewText: Match #1 Last Man Standing Match: CM Punk vs. Randy Orton  - 4.2/5.This match was really fun and awesome to watch. Both these guys pulled out all the spots and got awesome match out of it. Really cool spots in this one. Orton gets the win after an RKO off the top rope, after multiple shots from the cane.Match #2 Tables Match for the United States Championship: Sheamus vs. Kofi Kingston - 3/5Last minute match, but it was a heck of a match. Kofi came off the tope and leg dropped Sheamus through a table outside the ring. It looked awesome.Match #3 Country Whipping Match: Michael Cole & Jack Swagger vs. Jerry Lawler & Jim Ross  - 2/5Seriously? What could I say about this match? Cole and Swagger get the win.Match #4 Falls Count Anywhere Match: Cody Rhodes vs. Rey Mysterio -3.5/5I rememeber this match being really fun. This was a rematch from WMania27, which Cody won. Rey Mysterio gets the win and gets revenge on Cody Rhodes.Match #5 Loser Leaves WWE Match: Michelle McCool vs. Layla -2.5/5This was a pretty decent diva's match up. Layla gets the win, they both cry after the match. If this match is remembered for anything, it'll have to be thee debu of.. KHARMA. Comes out and lays out McCool.Match #6 Ladder Match for the Vacant World Heavyweight Championship: Christian vs. Alberto Del Rio - 4.5/5I loved this match, it was great. Edge had to vacant the title cause of his retirement. Del Rio already had match, but CHristian had to win a Battle Royal to earnt the shot. Lots of cool spots in this match. Brodus Clay gets busted open, hard way. Del Rio got distracted by Edge, Christian took adavntaged and won the Vacant World title. Very emotional moment.Match #7 Lumberjack for the WWE Tag Team Championships: Kane & Big Show vs. Wade Barrett & Ezekiel Jackson - 2.5/5Wasn't really a memorble match here. Show and Kane retain the Tag titles.(Main Event) Match #8 Triple Threat Steel Cage Match for the WWE Championship: The Miz vs. John Cena vs. Morrison -4/5A hell of a main event, Morrison was fantastic in this match. Everyone was good. Awesome spots from Morrison, of course. Miz took a crazy spot which he landed on his head. Interfernce from the now heel, R-Truth. Cena gets the win from AA from the top rope onto The Miz. Heck of a match.Extreme Rules was a great pay-per-view, they needed it after WMania27. One of the best PPVs of 2011. I give it a..8/10 stars.BluRay extas.- Edge's Retirement Speech from SD! 4/15/11- John Cena's Draft Night from RAW 4/25/11- The Rock's Birthday Celebration from RAW 5/2/11

reviewText: This year's addition of Extreme Rules was a pretty decent show, but considering how badly it was promoted and the fact that Osama Bin Laden was killed the night this show occured, I don't think anyone is going to remember it.  The undercard for the most part was average at best, but a good opener and two strong main events really saved the show from thumbs middle territory and turned it into a moderate thumbs up.  Matches are rated out of 5 stars (*****).1.  Last Man Standing MatchRandy Orton vs. C.M. PunkBefore the match started, Punk removed the turnbuckle pad, ala Diesel and Bret Hart at Survivor Series '95 (great match by the way).  This match was also very good.  Early on Punk attacked Orton with a kendo stick, but Orton eventually turned the tables and used the stick on Punk.  Orton then made his usual comeback, but Punk eventually catapulted him into the exposed buckle.  There was some nice action on the outside, as Orton whipped Punk back and forth between the apron and the dasher boards and then hit a powerslam on the floor, but Punk got to his feet before 10.  Orton cleared the announce table and backdropped Punk on the dasher boards in a cool spot.  Back in the ring the RKO was countered into a GTS, but Orton got his feet at 9.  Punk hit a nice russian leg sweep onto a chair, but Orton got to his feet again at 9.  Punk sat the chyair upright and tried another leg sweep but Orton hit an RKO, and Punk got his feet at 9 and rolled to the outside.  Orton tried a draping ddt off the dasher boards but Punk countered and posted Orton.  Punk then pillmanized Orton's neck with a chair by throwing it into the post, but Orton was up at 9.  Punk tried a GTS on the announce table but Orton countered it and hit an RKO, but the table didn't break, and Punk stood up at 8.  Orton then went for a punt but Punk sidestepped it and gave Orton a GTS on the stairs, which got a 9 count.  Punk slowly assended the top rope but Orton caught him and beat the hell out of him with the kendo stick.  Orton then climbed on top and hit an RKO off the top rope, and Punk was unable to stand for the 10 count, and Orton is the winner.  Very good opener.  ***1/22.  United States Championship Tables MatchSheamus (c) vs. Kofi KingstonThis match was added at the last minute, and absolutely nobody in the crowd cared about it at all.  This was just a way to balance the titles on both brands, because Sheamus and Barrett (the IC champ, for those who forgot), are both on Smackdown, so they needed to put a mid card belt on Raw.  The match was decent, but nothing special.  Sheamus went fpor a high cross on Kofi through a table early but it was countered.  At one point Sheamus was hanging off the apron about to fall through the table, but as Kofi ran at him he did a jumping shoulder block.  Sheamus used the table as a weapon, and even put it on top of Kofi and stood on it and celebrated.  It was Kofi's turn to dangle off the apron, and Sheamus hit a bro kick, but Kofi leaped over the table, which was a cool spot.  Eventually Sheamus was hit with the Trouble in Paradise to the outside, and as he stood up Kofi hit him with the boom drop off the top rope and put him through the table for the win.  The finish was awesome but the rest of the match was merely average.  **1/43.  Country Whipping MatchJim Ross & Jerry "the King" Lawler vs. Michael Cole & Jack SwaggerBasic concept of the match is that it's a normal tag match but the whips are legal.  Cole came out wearing bubble wrap so the whips wouldn't hurt him.  Early on Lawler and Ross tried whipping him but it had no effect, so Lawler just punched him and ripped off the wrap.  Cole would then quickly tag out and let Swagger do his dirty work.  Swagger bomb misses and Lawler went to work, but Cole distracted Lawler and Swagger locked on the ankle lock.  Ross then distracted Swagger and Lawler hit him with a beautiful DDT.  Ross tagged in and whipped swagger, then put Swagger in the ankle lock.  Swagger crawled over to his corner and tagged in Cole, and Ross just beat the hell out of him and put the ankle lock on him as well.  Swagger came in to break it up, but Ross nailed him with a low blow.  Cole then came up from behind and rolled up Ross for the three, which wasn't pretty looking.  The match was no good at all, but at least it was kept short.  Sadly it looks like this fued is going to continue.  *4.  Falls Count Anywhere MatchRey Mysterio vs. Cody RhodesThey brawled on the outside pretty much from the get go.  Rey hit a nice senton off the stage but only got a 2 count.  They brawled up the stands into the crowd, and Cody locked in a Walls of Jericho on Rey around the gaurd rail, which was a cool spot.  Eventually they worked their way to the concession area and they did some cool back and forth moves, jumping off things, etc., and the crowd backstage really liked it.  They worked their way back to the ring, and Cody hit an alabama slam for 2.  Cody had rey propped on the top rope, but Rey spit mist in Cody's eyes, and then hit a 619 and a splash for the clean win.  That was wacky.  Solid match, but nothing off the charts or anything.  The backstage stuff was very good.  **3/45.  No Disqualification Loser Leaves WWE MatchMichelle McCool vs. LaylaThey really tried here, but the crowd was COMPLETELY dead and it just wasn't working.  They tried having this epic match, but parts of it were very sloppy.  Finish came when McCool hit a styles clash, but Layla kicked out at 2.  Layla then cradled McCool for the win, and McCool is gone from wwe.  Match wasn't good, but they did try hard and it was probably better than most women's matches in WWE.  *1/46.  World Heavyweight Championship Ladder Match (Title is Vacant)Christian vs. Alberto Del Rio w/ Ricardo RodriguezThis marks only the third time that whoever wins the match will be champion for the first time, the other two occasions being Randy Savage vs. Ted Dibiase at Wrestlemania IV, and the Rock vs. Mankind at Survivor Series 1998 9both of those were tournament finals).  This was a great match with some brutal spots.  They did some of the usual spots, such as dropkicking ladders into each other.  Del Rio took a nasty backdrop onto a ladder as well.  At one point Christian was climbing, but Del Rio put a smaller ladder next to Christian's ladder and did a jumping armbreaker on Christian off the ladder.  Christian went on top of a ladder in the ring, but Del Rio hit a gorgeous running enziguiri on Christian and Christian fell down with the ladder and landed on it.  On the outside Rodriguez came Del Rio a chair, but Christian posted him.  Bsck in the ring Christian set up for an Edge-like spear, with taunt and all, and he hit it and the crowd went nuts.  They had a ladder set up from the apron to the announce table, and after some brawling outside, Del Rio set Christian up on it.  Del Rio went up top and tried to leg drop Christian on the ladder, but he moved out of the way and Del Rio just crashed onto the ladder in an awesome spot.  With Del Rio deceased, Christian set the ladder up and was about to climb and win, but as he reached the gold Brodus Clay came out and grabbed his legs.  Christian eventually got the better of him and pushed him into a ladder in the corner, busting Brodus open hardway, and he was absolutely GUSHING blood.  Del Rio got back in the ring and locked the armbar on Christian through a ladder.  Del Rio then climbed up and was about to win, but Edge came out in a jeep and honked the horn to distract Del Rio.  As Del Rio was distracted, Christian got to his feet and knocked the ladder over, sending Del Rio crashing to the floor on top of Rodriguez and a bloody Brodus.  Christian then ascended the ladder and grabbed the gold, winning his first heavyweight title in WWE.  After the match, Edge and Christian embraced and celebrated together, and the crowd loved every minute of this.  This was a case where WWE gave the fans exactly what they wanted to see, and the entire thing was great.  ****7.  Tag Team Championship Lumberjack MatchBig Show (c) & Kane (c) vs. Wade Barrett & Ezekial JacksonLooking at this match on paper is cringeworthy, and it wasn't much better when it actually started.  They did the usual lumberjack spots where guys get thrown outside and beat up, and it was no good.  The lumberjacks were all jobbers of course.  Finish came when Barrett tagged himself in, which angered Zeke.  Barrett then tried to give Big Show the wasteland, but Big Show countered and hit a chokeslam for the 3.  Match was mercifully short, but pretty awful while it lasted.  3/4*8.  WWE Championship Triple Threat Cage MatchThe Miz (c) vs. John Cena vs. John MorrisonThis was a really good match.  They did some nice threeway spots early, with the usual one man isolation.  Cena hit a bulldog off the top rope on Miz, and then quickly hit 3 of the 5 moves of doom on Morrison.  Miz came up from behind and hit Cena with the Skull Crushing Finale.  Morrison tried to escape, but Miz ran up and caught him.  Cena worked his way up the cage as well, and he and Morrison hit an absolutely horryfing double suplex on Miz off the top of the cage.  Cena did a horrible job protecting Miz, and Miz landed right on his head.  I thought he was dead, but somehow he survived.  Morrison hit an awesome C4 on Cena but that only gets 2.  Morrison tried to escape, but the Miz caught him and powerbombed him hard into the cage.  Cena locked the STF on Miz but Miz crawled to the door and Cena had to break the hold.  Both men then went back and forth trying to crawl out the door.  While the door was open, Morrison went up top but got crotched on the open door, and Miz dragged him inside.  After some more battling Morrison climbed on top, but instead of trying to leave he hit a starship pain off the top of the cage onto Cena and Miz.  Morrison was about to win through the door, but R-Truth came out and knee'd him in the head and threw him back inside.  Truth then pummeled Morrison into oblivion, including giving him a downward spiral.  Truth also hit Cena with an ax-kick, and then symbolically climbed over the top of the cage as if to say had he been in the match, he would have won.  Truth did a great job here.  All three men were dead inside the ring.  Miz got to his feet first and tried to escape over the top, but Cena caught him and they battled on top of the cage.  Eventually Cena won the battle, and hit Miz with an Attitude Adjustment off the top rope for the win and his 10th (yes) heavyweight championship.  ***3/4During the middle of this show I was not particularly enjoying it, but by the end of the show, thanks to the two great main events, I wound up liking the show.  I would recommend seeing the show if you have not, if only for the Last Man Standing Match, the Ladder Match, and the Cage match, all of which were very good.

reviewText: Extreme Rules:1. Randy Orton vs Cmpunk Last Man Standing Match: This was a great opener, quite a few weapons used, a lot of good spots and the tempo of the match was excellent, the match went on for 19 mins so it was given a lot of time, the ending to the match was great but I am a little dissapointed about the outcome ***3/42. Sheamus(c) vs Kofi Kingston U.S Title Table Match: This was another good match, it had a lot of teasers with the tables and told a great story, this is a good match for a 10 min match ***1/43. Michael Cole/Jack Swagger vs Jerry Lawler vs/Jim Ross Country Whipping Match: This was horrendous, jim ross is the worst that i've ever seen in the ring, cole sucks and so does lawler, the match went on for 7 mins and it seemed like it went on forever, just skip this match *4. Rey Mysterio vs Cody Rhodes Falls Count Anywhere: This was another really good match, they brawled everywhere, the pace was good, but the ending seemed out of place, but anyway this is a very good match ***1/25. Christian vs Alberto Del Rio WH Title Ladder Match: This is the match of the night by far, this was excellent, so many great spots with the ladder, a very fast paced match for a 20 min match, del rio takes a nasty bump when he misses a legdrop and hits the ladder that was pout on the announce table and ring apron, clay gets involved towards the end and takes a hard shot from the ladder by christian, this busts him open and at the end of the match you see the blood over the ringside floor pouring out of his head, it was cool to see on a PG show! The ending was very memerable, I loved the outcome, christian has worked his ass off in the WWE for 11 years and on this PPV he finally gets the breakthrough he deserves, overall a great match ****1/46. Big Show/Kane(c) vs Wade Barret/ Eziekal Jackson WWE Tag Team Titles Lumberjack Match: Who cares about this match, waste of time! *1/47. Miz(c) vs John Cena vs John Morrison WWE Title Steel Cage Match: This was a very good main event, this was another 20 minute match and it didnt dissapoint, they used the cage well and was kept at a good tempo, R-Truth interfered at the end and WWE actually made him look important which was nice to see, I wasnt suprsised with the outcome, and I think we all know now that The Rock vs John Cena will be for the WWE Title at Wrestlemania 28 ***3/4Match of the Night: WH Title MatchWorst Match of Night: Country Whipping MatchMoment of Night: Christian wins a major title!!!Overall PPV: 8.25/10Very enjoyable show!!!

reviewText: All you need to know is that if you are a wrestling fan, especially a John Cena fan like I am, then this is a must buy for you. This is the best wrestling ppv i've seen in a long time. Every single match is great except for the one between J.R./Lawler and Cole/Swagger. In fact this is one of the best ppv's i've ever seen and is definantly better than Wrestlemania 27 but Wrestlemania 27 is great as well in my opinion. Even if you are against the whole "PG" era you still should give this event a shot.
